ique, exceptional, newsworthy events, it is a mistake to think of disasters as isolated or discrete occurrences. Rather, building on insights developed by political ecologists, this book makes a compelling argument for understanding disasters as transnational and global phenomena.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBankoff, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrios, Roberto E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrinaga, George Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButton, Gregory V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButton, Gregory V., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChecker, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEldridge, Erin R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazrus, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLove, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarino, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParson, Nia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuller, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuller, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311099822140uhttps://doi.org/10.151